{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_american_ver02/data/sn86072041/00211108691/1908020801/0140.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nBEST\nADV.\nMEDIUM\nVOL. 111. NO. 196.\nCook With Electricity\nA little disc stove which can be set on your table, and in which\nyou can quickly heat water orcook is a great convenience. Free\ntrial.\nWenatchee Electric Co.\nSAVINGS ACCOUNTS\nLargest\nCapital\nof any\nBank\nin\nNorth\nCentral\nWashington\nCapital\n$100,000,\nOldest\nBank in\nNorth\nCentral\nWashington\nEstablished\n1802\nColumbia Valley\nBuy a Home Site in\nGRAND\nVIEW\nEasy Terms\u2014sso Down and $10 a Month\nWenatchee Realty and Invest\nment Company\n\"BELMONT\"\nBy The Bridge\nMost popular addition ever placed on market.\nOver six thousand dollars worth of these lots sold in the\nlast thirty days; more than in all other additions com\nbined. Nearly all gone. Get in on these lots at original\nowner's prices.\nLots, large, 7>o x 148 feet, with trees, perpetual water\nright, sightly, overlooking tl river, the bridge and the\nalfalfa fields and orchards o> ::ast Wenatchee.\nPrice, from $300 to $100 per lot; terms, $10. 820, $35\ndown; $10 to $lo per month.\nPERCY WALKER, Owner.\nWALKER WIDNEY, Agents\nVk Wails Motlh\nA savings Account in\nthis old, strong bank\nis a good investment,\navailable on short\nnotice in time of need\nand perfectly safe.\nBank\nWENATC HEE, WASH.\nTHE WENATCHEE DAILY WORLD, WENATCHEE, WASHINGTO X, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 8, 1908.\n0. S. SENATORS BY DIRECT VOTE\nMALAGA WANTS\nA STATION\nResidents of that Place Take Up the\nMatter with Railroad Commis\nsion.\nThe people of Malaga believe that\nthey are entitled to a depot and bet\nter station facilities, and have,\nthrough attorneys Corbin, Ludington\nKemp, laid their needs before the\nstate railroad commission, with the\nresult that a complaint is being pre\npared by the commission requiring\nthe Great Northern Railroad to show\ncause why their wishes in the matter\nshould not be complied with.\nThere are five months in the year\nwhen a great deal of express ship-1\nments are made. While there is a lit j\ntie express shed, tne facilities arej\nvery inadequate. During the ship-:\nping season at least three men are\nkept busy.\nThe case of the State vs. Ed Ca-'\nrey of Cashmere, in which the lat- j\nter is charged with having sold liq-i\nuor to an habitual drunkard, has j\nbeen continued. The defendant, j\nthrough his attorney, Ira Thomas,!\nmoved the court for a continuance I\ntill Feb. 14.\nLOCAL MENTION\nI Mr. and Mrs. Luddington, recent\n'ly from Illinois, are now settled it\ntheir home at 320 King street.\nThe girls of St. Agnes Guild wil\nmeet this afternoon at the home 61\nthe Misses Keane on Douglas street\n\nJ Dr. L. E. Hutchinson is in Seattle\nlon a several days' visit in attendance\ni upon a meeting of the Alumni ol\nj his dental fraternity.\ni The most complete line of Hot\nWater Bottles, Syringes and Bnbbei\nGoods in the city at the Wenatchee\nDrug Co.\nJ. B. Smith, who has been critically\ni ill at his home in Belmont Addition,\nis much improved. His complete re\ncovery is believed to be close at hand.\nA good house attended the Horse\nshoe Theater last nigbr am*\" enjoyed\nj the usual fine entertainment. The\nmoving pictures were exceptional\nI fine and Hart Mack entertained\n!the audience with their comedian\nl features.\nThe members of the B. P. Club\nj were guests of Mr. and Mrs. Frank\nCase at their home on Chelan ave\nnue Xorth last evening. The usual\npastime of 500 was afforded those\npresent.\nI\nAMONG THE CHURCHES\ni\nMethodist Church.\nServices at usual hours. Preach\ning at 11 a. m. and 7:30 p. m.\nMorning subject, \"Baptism.\" The\nsacrament of baptism will be ad\nministered at the morning service.\nI Evening subject, \"A Frequent Visi\ntor.\" Sunday school at 10 a. m.,\nJunior League at 3 p. m., Epworth\nLeague at 6:30 p. m. The evening\nservice will be evangelistic. All are\ninvited.\nH. L. BEIG-HTOL, Pastor.\nEpiscopalian Church.\nThe usual services will be held\nin St. Luke's Episcopal church on\ntomorrow (Sunday) at 11 a. m. and\n7 p. m. Sunday school 9:,45 a. m.\nA cordial invitation is extended to\nall to attend these services. Good\nmusic and a hearty service.\nT. A. HILTOX, Rector.\nPresbyterian hurch.\n9:4-) a. m., Bible School, Mr. How\nard Thomas, superintendent.\n11a. m., morning Worship; ser\nmon by the minister, \"The Cross.\"\n6:30 p. m.. Christian Endeavor\nSociety.\n7:30 p. m., Special Evangelitsic\nService led by the minister: subject,\n\"The Two Builders.\" Choir music;\nall welcome.\nJXO. W. BERGER, Minitsor.\nFirst Baptist hurdi.\nBible School, 10 a. m.; preaching,\n11 a. m. and 7:30 p. m.; B. Y. P. U.\n6:30 p. m.; junior, 3 p. m., Sa itrday;\nprayer and bible study. Thursday,\n7:30 p. m. Sermon topics, a. m.,\n\"Our Lord's Prayer:\" evening, an\nevangelistic service topic, \"The ele\nments of strength.\" Congregational\nsinging. A cordial invitation to all\nto worship with us.\nE. O. JESSUP,' Pastor.\nCase is Continued.\nEXPRESS YOUR\nVIEWS ON THE\nSENATORSHIP\nNext week the Daily World will\ndevote some space to the discus\nsion of the United States Senator\nship. At present there are two\ncandidates before the people.\nThese are the present incumbent,\nLevi P. Ankeny, and Congressman\nWesley L. Jones now of the\nLower House.\nWesley L. Jones has made a\ngood record in the House, and\nthinks he is entitled to the sen\natorship. Levi P. Ankeny, on the\nother hand, believes that he is\nentitled to go back to the Senate\non account of his former work.\nThe Daily World represents it\nself as the mouthpiece of the peo\nple of this section, and, as such,\nits columns are open to YOU for\nan expression of your opinion.\nBelmont is Booming.\nj Eight new houses are in process\njof construction or soon to begin in\nj the Belmont addition. J. H. Geyer\nthis week begins a new building in\nthis addition. Emilin Houghton is j\nj now hauling lumber preparatory to\nbuilding a two-story residence. W.\nW. I'lin is just completing a two- j\nstory residence.\nJustus B. Smith is preparing to\nbuild a large addition to his present\nresidence. Other houses are in con\ntemplation for the spring and early\nsummer.\nJ Land Office lean Dp in Spring.\nAc report from Olympia says: A3\nsoon as the-~winter breaks In East\nern Washington. Land Commission\ner Ross will s<yid a large force of\nstate land inspectors into the field,\nespecially in Chelan and northeasi\ncounties to clear up all pending ap- 1\nplications for state land which have\ni been accumulating for months.\nThe commissioner also contem\nplates making a segregation in his\noffice of all lands suitable only as|\ngrazing lands to expedite the appli\ncation and inspection of land applied\nfor as grazing land.\nREAD LIKES\nLAKE CHELAN\nEastern Washington and especial\nly Lake Chelan seems to have hit\nOpie Read a great deal harder than\nthe recent financial panic did. He\ntalks about the lake country every\nwhere he goes. Lying in bed in a\nSeattle hotel nursing his painful feet\nswollen and inflamed with rheuma\ntism, Mr. Read entertained a pro\ncession of visitors with his inexhaus\ntible fund of happy stories and anec\ndotes. Mention of the recent finan\ncial panic by a newspaper reporter\nwho was among his callers, remind\ned him of the remarkable material\nprosperity of the Inland Empire,\nand that in turn brought to mind\nhis recent visit to Lake Chelan. He\nis reported as saying:\n\"The financial panic in Xew York\ndidn't worry me in the least, because\nI don't recollect of having enouch\nmoney to be seriously damaged by\nany such a proceeding.\n\"The panic is over and the state\nof Washington felt its effects far\nless than any o s state I have\ntraveled through. Eastern Wash\nington is the richest empire I ever\nsaw. I was particularly pleased\nwith Lake Chelan. Think of an in\nland lake sixty-five miles long, at\none end a glacier and the other a\npeach orchard!\"\nIt was evident that a good invest\nment was made for the people of\nthe Chelan valley when Opie Read\nwas selectet as one of the Etude\nclub's lecturers; not only did he\ngive those ,v.ho patronize the course\ntheir moneys worth, but he is giv-j\ning the valley a lot of free and en-j\nthusiastic advertising. Chelan\nLeader.\nTO-NIGHT B;3o\u2014Horseshoe Theatre, Louis Michel, Prop.,~Hart\nMack, I Illie Mullen and Choice Moving Pictures, Prices the Same, 15 25c\nBUSINESS COLLEGE PICTURE OE TEACHERS AXD SCHOLARS IX COLORS.\nDaily World Takes Up Question\nWith Washington Senators and\nRepresentatives Generally sin\nFavor of It.\nWhy should the members of the\nCnited States Senate oppose the will\njof the people in reference to the\nI election of senators by direct vote?\ni Time after time, the lower house has\ntaken up the question of ordering\nan election for the purpose of amend\nj ing the constitution of the United\nStates giving the people the right\n!to select their man for the high of\nfice of senator by direct vote. Just\nas many times as they have brought\n;up the question, just that many\ntimes has it been turned down by\nthe senate.\nTo ascertain the feeling of the\nWashington delegation, 'the World\nhas addressed a letter to each one,\nasking his opinion on the question.\nj Following is the result:\nHumphrey Favors it.\nWashington, D. C, Jan. 27.\nMr. Rufus Woods, Editor World\ni Advance Publishing Co., Wenat\nchee, Wash.:\nDear Sir\u2014l am in receipt of your\nletter asking me whether or not I\nam in favor of the election of Unit\ned States Senators by the direct\nvote of the people. I am, yours\ntruly,\nW. E. HUMPHREY. M. C.\nJones Heartily in Favor of It.\nWashington, D. C, Jan. 27.'\n.Mr. Rufus Woods, Edtor World-Ad\nj vance, Wenatchee, Wash.\nSIMPICH IS DESIGNATED\nFOE CONSULAR SERVICE\nRecent Editor of the Daily World\nReceives Advices From Wash\nington Will Take Examination\nAbout April 1.\ni\nFred Simpich, formerly editor ofr\nthis paper, is in receipt of advices\nfrom Washington, D. C, that he has!\ni (been designated by Secretary of'\nState Elihn H. Root for examination\nfor appointment in the United States I\nconsular service.\nj Mr. Simpich has had an experi-'\nence both in the United States and\nin foreign lands, which especially!\nfits him for any position in the con-\nsular service. His knowledge of\npeople and subjects is broad. This, 1\ntogether with the fact that he is a\nyoung man of energy and character,\nsecured for him the endorsement of\n\u25a0Washington's representatives la\nj Congress and his local friends.\nA DELIGHTFUL\nKENSINGTON\nI Mrs. C. M. Deniston was \"at\nhome\" with Mrs. A. A. Piper at the\nresidence of the latter on Wenat\nchee avenue to a large circle of their\n1 friends yesterday afternoon.\nI The ladies were asked to bring\ntheir sewing and enjoy a pleasant\nhour at Kensington work, after\nwhich they were entertained by mak\ning valentines and writing the\nverses thereto. Mrs. J. J. Clapp se\ncured the first prize, a pretty valen\ntine, for constructing the most ar\ntistic message from that popular\nsaint, and Mrs. E. M. Allen proved\n'herself an adept with the comic se-\nA delicious hot luncheon was\nserved by the entertainers at a late j\nhour and ended a delightful afcer\njnoon. Those invited were:\nMesdames Frank Reeves, E. M.\nj Allen, W. A. Thompson, Leroy\nWright, H. E. Fenton. H. H. Whita\n-1 ker, O. E. Loying, John Berger, A.\nREAD\nTHE\nWANT\nADS.\nFIVE CENTS PERCOrr.\nI My Dear Sir\u2014Your favor of the\n20th instant, asking me whether or\nnot I am in favor of the election of\nUnited States senators by the direct\nvote of the people, at hand.\ni am heartily in favor of this\nproposition. Our legislature has ex\npressed itself along these lines sev\neral times, and this is one reason\nwhy I am in favor of our di\nrect primary law. It ,in fact,\ncomes as near providing for the\nelection of senators by the people\nand, when you come to consider it,\nit is in practical working substan\ntially the same as the selection of\nsenators by the people, because if\nwe had the constitution changed, the\nselection would be made by each\nparty nominating its own candidate\nfor the senate and the people vot\ning for them at the election. The\nlaw now provides for the nomina\ntion for senator by each party and\nI have no doubf but that, in voting\nfor members of the legislature, the\npeople have the right to feel that\ntheir expressed choice at the primary\nwill receive the votes of their mem\nbers of the legislature on the re\nspective party tickets, so that there\ncan be but little doubt, but that if\nthe legislature is republican it will\nelect the choice of the republican\n(Continued on Page 2.)\nMr. Simpich resided for a year or\ntwo in Japan and China, and was\nfor some time editor of the Manila\nAmerican, and later manager of the\nTimes, at Manila, P. I. He was also\nthe representative in the Orient of\ndifferent American newspapers.\nThe U. S. consular service,\nthrough the efforts of Roosevelt, has\nbeen placed on the \"merit system\"\nbasis, and all examinations are com\npetitive.\nSimpich leaves here tomorrow for\na week's visit in Portland, when he\nwill return here and prepare for the\nexaminations, which are held at\nWashington, D. C, by the State De\npartment about April 1.\nM. Wilson, H. L. Parshall, W. L.\nMoseley, Sarah Clapp, B. C. Collier,\nE. A. Nichols, Katheryne Hayne, C.\nE. Battles, A. N. Corbin, R. F. Holm,\nJ. J. Clapp, W. W. Gray, E. M. Tup\nper, D. H. King. Zelma Hines, F. R.\nEvans, E. H. Preece, \"'am Merriam,\nS. A. Thompson, U. G. Pogue.\nI Fresh Palm Candy received each\nweek at the Wenatcnee Drag Co.\n\nj C. C. Hurlburt, better known as\ni \"Mississip,\" formerly connected\nwiih the city engineer's office. Is\nback to Wenatchee again after an\nJ absence of some weeks in Northern\nIdaho. He reports the weather\namong the Coeur d'Alenes as being\n]20 degrees below zero, and he was\non one of the lake steamers when it\nI was frozen in the ice and the pas\nsengers were forced to find other\nI means of conveyance.\nThe Ladies' Aid of the Baptist\nchurch will serve a chicken dinner\nlon Washington's birthday.\nStockton's Coli-Zona for Kidney,\nLiver and Stomach trouble for sale\nat the Wenatchee Drug Co.","height":"22506","width":"15828"}}
